SIMPLE: remedy
RECORDS: 2

==== ENTRY 1 ====
HEADWORD: Remedy
<hw>Rem"e*dy</hw> <pr>(r?m"?-d?)</pr>, <pos>n.</pos>; <plu><it>pl.</it>
<plw>Remedies</plw> <pr>(-d<?/z)</pr>.</plu> <ety>[L.
<ets>remedium</ets>; pref. <ets>re-</ets> re- + <ets>mederi</ets> to
heal, to cure: cf. F. <ets>rem⟦egrave⟧de</ets> remedy,
<ets>rem⟦eacute⟧dier</ets> to remedy. See <er>Medical</er>.]</ety>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>1.</sn> <def>That which relieves or cures a disease; any medicine
or application which puts an end to disease and restores health; -- with
<xex>for</xex>; <as>as, a <ex>remedy</ex> for the gout</as>.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>2.</sn> <def>That which corrects or counteracts an evil of any
kind; a corrective; a counteractive; reparation; cure; -- followed by
<xex>for</xex> or <xex>against</xex>, formerly by
<xex>to</xex>.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>What may else be <qex>remedy</qex> or cure⟦br⟧
To evils which our own misdeeds have wrought,⟦br⟧
He will instruct us.</q> <rj><qau>Milton.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>3.</sn> <fld>(Law)</fld> <def>The legal means to recover a right,
or to obtain redress for a wrong.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><cs><col><b>Civil remedy</b></col>. <cd>See under
<er>Civil</er>.</cd> -- <col><b>Remedy of the mint</b></col>
<fld>(Coinage)</fld>, <cd>a small allowed deviation from the legal
standard of weight and fineness; -- called also
<altname>tolerance</altname>.</cd></cs>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><syn><b>Syn.</b> -- Cure; restorative; counteraction; reparation;
redress; relief; aid; help; assistance.</syn>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Remedy</ent>⟦br⟧

==== ENTRY 2 ====
HEADWORD: Remedy
<hw>Rem"e*dy</hw>, <pos>v. t.</pos> <vmorph>[<pos>imp. & p. p.</pos>
<conjf>Remedied</conjf> <pr>(-d?d)</pr>; <pos>p. pr. & vb. n.</pos>
<conjf>Remedying</conjf>.]</vmorph> <ety>[L. <ets>remediare</ets>,
<ets>remediari</ets>: cf. F. <ets>rem⟦eacute⟧dier</ets>. See
<er>Remedy</er>, <pos>n.</pos>]</ety> <def>To apply a remedy to; to
relieve; to cure; to heal; to repair; to redress; to correct; to
counteract.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>I will <qex>remedy</qex> this gear ere long.</q>
<rj><qau>Shak.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Remelt</ent>⟦br⟧
